WEST NILE VIRUS - ISRAEL
************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 10 Aug 2014
Source: Arutz Sheva [edited]
http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/Flash.aspx/301189#.U-k1I67th9F


The Israeli Health Ministry on Sunday [10 Aug 2014] reported that 3 diagnosed cases of West Nile virus [infection], a mosquito-borne disease, were recorded in Israel over the course of last month [July 2014].

Up until the July [2014] cases, the total number of patients suffering from the virus since the start of the year was at 15, with 2 of them being diagnosed cases and the remaining 13 suspected as being [caused by] the virus.

The cases stretched through a region from the Haifa and Afula area in the north of the country to the Ashkelon region in the south and were reported in 12 different communities. In the central Gush Dan coastal region, 6 patients suffering from the virus have been reported up till now.

While most people infected with the virus either experience no symptoms or only minor ones, such as a fever or mild headache, the virus is life-threatening to some and can develop into an inflammation of the brain. Severe symptoms, such as a severe headache, fever or disorientation, require immediate attention.

In 2013, 71 cases of the virus were reported in Israel; 4 of those infected passed away from the disease. Likewise in 2012, out of a total of 89 cases, 2 patients passed away.

The Ministry of Health recommends that the public protect itself by avoiding mosquito bites through various means, including the usage of mosquito repellent creams, placing screens on windows, and reporting standing stagnant water to local authorities, given that stagnant water is often a breeding ground for the insects.

The virus reportedly resides in birds; mosquitoes who bite birds carrying the virus can transmit it to humans.

In around one per cent of cases, the virus poses a serious danger. There is no specific treatment for the virus, and, therefore, the main method to combat it is by avoiding contracting the disease, primarily by preventing mosquito bites.

[Byline: Yishai Karov, Ari Yashar]

